Three police officers have been confirmed dead after they were ambushed by armed bandits on Wednesday within the Laikipia Nature Conservancy.  Speaking to The Standard, Rift Valley Regional Police Commander Fred Ochieng’ said the officers were on normal patrol when they encountered the bandits.  “We lost three officers on Wednesday morning after they were ambushed by bandits. Two other officers sustained injuries after a fire exchange before the bandits vanished,” said Ochieng’.  This brings the total number of police officers killed in the ongoing security operation to four. A national police reservist and 11 civilians have also lost their lives in the last two months.    Lamu Senator Anwar Loitiptip to spend night in police custody  Trench to mitigate banditry, human-wildlife conflict in Laikipia  Scars of banditry in Kerio Valley: How attacks have yielded widows and poverty  Special command team to take over Laikipia security operation Ochieng’ added that more officers were deployed to rescue their colleagues but the car they travelling in was involved in an accident.  "The six officers injured in the ambush and the accident have been airlifted to Nairobi for treatment,” said Ochieng’.   CS Fred Matiang'i says the Government is committed to addressing the insecurity in Laikipia County  Kamket Kizimbani: Mbunge wa Tiaty amekamatwa jana kuhusiana na mapigano eneo la Laikipia  Laikipia county Gov't enters into a lease agreement to enable it scale-up infrastructure development By Peter Ochieng  | 34 minutes ago By Nikko Tanui | 1 hour ago By Julius Chepkwony | 12 hours ago By Nikko Tanui | 12 hours ago